President Barack Obama welcomed Mohammad Ashraf Ghani, President of Afghanistan, and Chief Executive Abdullah Abdullah, to Washington to discuss the progress made in Afghanistan over the past 13 years and to renew the U.S.-Afghan partnership. They discussed the need for sustained U.S. and international assistance to address the security challenges facing Afghanistan and the region. The leaders also emphasized the importance of promoting democratic values, advancing long-term security, strengthening the peace process, reinforcing regional security and cooperation, and fostering social and economic development in Afghanistan. They agreed to work together to improve Afghan institutions and governance, combat corruption, and uphold the rule of law. Overall, the visit highlighted the achievements and challenges of the U.S.-Afghan partnership and laid the groundwork for a continued and sustained relationship.